mpact on contemporary Canada and highlight the contested, sometimes exclusionary nature of the movement itself. Insights from gender and women’s studies, cultural and literary theory, social psychology, and sociology infuse Feeling Feminism as the contributors explore how emotions shaped and nourished feminist activism. More generally, they demonstrate the power of emotions, desires, and actions to transform the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAffect (Psychology)xSocial aspectszCanada. 0aEmotionsxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aFeminismzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSecond-wave feminismzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aAladejebi, Funké, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntoniazzi, Taylor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeck, Marin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrun, Josette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrushett, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Lara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Lara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDawson, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDawson, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDoucet, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFesnak, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGentile, Patrizia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGidney, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGidney, Catherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 